{"componentChunkName":"component---src-templates-post-template-js","path":"/cloud9-editor","webpackCompilationHash":"0dbc1e07081b2fda90ea","result":{"data":{"markdownRemark":{"id":"aa0b65cb-0b92-5bb1-b515-8a044731438b","html":"<p><span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;  max-width: 512px;\"\n    >\n      <a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/static/68e8b9a27626b1be684e1da626cf950f/c5a17/cloud9-logo.png\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n    <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 100%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/png;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <picture>\n        <source\n          srcset=\"/static/68e8b9a27626b1be684e1da626cf950f/01472/cloud9-logo.webp 240w,\n/static/68e8b9a27626b1be684e1da626cf950f/222bd/cloud9-logo.webp 480w,\n/static/68e8b9a27626b1be684e1da626cf950f/c0b70/cloud9-logo.webp 512w\"\n          sizes=\"(max-width: 512px) 100vw, 512px\"\n          type=\"image/webp\"\n        />\n        <source\n          srcset=\"/static/68e8b9a27626b1be684e1da626cf950f/0783d/cloud9-logo.png 240w,\n/static/68e8b9a27626b1be684e1da626cf950f/782f4/cloud9-logo.png 480w,\n/static/68e8b9a27626b1be684e1da626cf950f/c5a17/cloud9-logo.png 512w\"\n          sizes=\"(max-width: 512px) 100vw, 512px\"\n          type=\"image/png\"\n        />\n        <img\n          class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n          src=\"/static/68e8b9a27626b1be684e1da626cf950f/c5a17/cloud9-logo.png\"\n          alt=\"Cloud9 editor logo\"\n          title=\"Cloud9 editor logo\"\n          loading=\"lazy\"\n        />\n      </picture>\n  </a>\n    </span></p>\n<p>Few months ago I attended a <a href=\"https://medium.com/@kalin.chernev/coding-battle-at-microsoft-innovation-center-brussels-the-rise-of-the-bots-f0887c15e257\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener noreferrer\">coding competition</a>. In the end of the event the winners demonstrated one of their tools: the <a href=\"https://c9.io\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener noreferrer\">Cloud9 editor</a>. Then it hit me — I had to experiment with it! Later I used it working on various projects in my free time. Here I’m going to share my experience so far — I’m a happy user :)</p>\n<h3 id=\"cloud9-is-great\"><a href=\"#cloud9-is-great\" aria-label=\"cloud9 is great permalink\" class=\"anchor\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a>Cloud9 is great</h3>\n<p>So far, I’ve found several key points/facts why I consider the editor to be truly astounding tool:</p>\n<ol>\n<li>Accessibility and User/Developer experience</li>\n<li><a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pair_programming\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener noreferrer\">Pair programming</a> and education</li>\n<li>Collaboration and open source</li>\n</ol>\n<h3 id=\"accessibility\"><a href=\"#accessibility\" aria-label=\"accessibility permalink\" class=\"anchor\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a>Accessibility</h3>\n<p>The tool is currently <a href=\"https://c9.io/pricing\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener noreferrer\">free</a> and <a href=\"https://github.com/c9\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener noreferrer\">open source</a>. Even if you’re not a technical person you already have reason #1 to either make a <a href=\"https://c9.io/signup\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener noreferrer\">new registration</a> or use your existing code-oriented account to <a href=\"https://c9.io/login\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener noreferrer\">log in</a> to the service. (No affiliation in the links) If you are non-technical, but very business person, you might know that Amazon will probably grow Cloud9 in the future.</p>\n<p>On the other hand, if you are a technical person and you take a closer look, you’ll see that it’s a charming service of <a href=\"https://ace.c9.io/#nav=about\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener noreferrer\">ace</a> which directly accesses <a href=\"https://www.docker.com/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener noreferrer\">docker</a> instances. The first time I showed a working <a href=\"https://docs.c9.io/docs/create-a-workspace\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener noreferrer\">workspace</a> to a friend developer telling him to use the environment just as Ubuntu — the response was something like</p>\n<p><img src=\"/141462efd4d89f3f9d011f2bc757fd42/mind-blowing.gif\" alt=\"It&#x27;s mind blowing!\"></p>\n<p>Later, he setup all his bash aliases and specific configurations and started to work with the terminal just as he’s working with his own Linux machine :)</p>\n<h3 id=\"pair-programming-and-education\"><a href=\"#pair-programming-and-education\" aria-label=\"pair programming and education permalink\" class=\"anchor\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a>Pair programming and education</h3>\n<p>As soon as the environment was ready (understand having all the aliases and custom shell scripts, drush, drupal console, etc. cli tools) we went into using some of the <a href=\"https://docs.c9.io/docs/share-a-workspace#section-collaboration-features\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener noreferrer\">collaboration features</a>. I will not put a meme here, but I’ll tell you this: the experience is very similar to using Google Drive for collaborating on documents in real-time, so if you like this — you’ll surely like this real-time coding experience too!</p>\n<p><a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pair_programming\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener noreferrer\">Pair programming</a> on same git branch and code base is not something we usually do for various reasons, but if you like doing it, or you need to do it — I’d definitely recommend you Cloud9. You can pair program remotely just as you’d normally do on 1 computer: sharing terminal, files, git branches, etc.</p>\n<p>From these pair program opportunities come also very interesting education opportunities. For example, <a href=\"https://cs50.harvard.edu/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener noreferrer\">CS50</a> and <a href=\"https://www.freecodecamp.com/challenges/start-a-nodejs-server\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener noreferrer\">freeCodeCamp</a>. These are good case studies of the cloud editor to encourage people of all walks of life to give programming a try and learn their <a href=\"https://docs.c9.io/docs/supported-languages\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener noreferrer\">preferred programming language</a> without any special computer hardware requirements, i.e. they can code real applications in the browser.</p>\n<h3 id=\"collaboration-and-open-source\"><a href=\"#collaboration-and-open-source\" aria-label=\"collaboration and open source permalink\" class=\"anchor\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a>Collaboration and open source</h3>\n<p>Because the service is free and very fun to use, it’s naturally an optional tool when working on various projects requiring tight collaboration such as open source projects.</p>\n<p>For example, I decided to work on <a href=\"https://github.com/Surnet/swagger-jsdoc\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener noreferrer\">swagger-jsdoc</a> node module which I used for a small project. All I had to do to make a pull request is:</p>\n<ol>\n<li>Make a new workspace (new virtual machine in the cloud)</li>\n<li>Git clone the fork repository</li>\n<li>Create a new branch and do your task</li>\n<li>Push back to fork repository and open a pull request</li>\n</ol>\n<p>Note that I didn’t even have to install any software, all I had to make this contribution was to open my browser and use Cloud9 as a cloud service.</p>\n<h3 id=\"keybindings\"><a href=\"#keybindings\" aria-label=\"keybindings permalink\" class=\"anchor\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a>Keybindings</h3>\n<p>These are some of the items I’m using quite often and sometimes get a WOW effect from people watching me doing things like that in my browser:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"https://docs.c9.io/docs/multiple-cursors\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener noreferrer\">Multiple cursors</a> (yep, <a href=\"https://www.sublimetext.com/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener noreferrer\">sublime</a> is to blame for our expectations)</li>\n<li>Command line tricks work just well (Ctrl+U, Ctrl+L)</li>\n<li><a href=\"https://docs.c9.io/docs/keybindings\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener noreferrer\">Find in tree</a> (and others)</li>\n<li><a href=\"https://docs.c9.io/docs/find-and-replacing-in-files#find-in-files\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener noreferrer\">Search/Find</a> is handy working with namespaces</li>\n</ul>\n<p>I think normally people don’t expect a full IDE experience in the browser, as I didn’t too, and that’s the reason I mentioned Docked previously for an eye-opener. Just by the way, PHP developers might be even more surprised with things like <del>xdebugger being available in their development environments</del> (xdebug seems not to be supported any more after the acquision at AWS).</p>\n<h3 id=\"setting-up-drupal-8\"><a href=\"#setting-up-drupal-8\" aria-label=\"setting up drupal 8 permalink\" class=\"anchor\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a>Setting up Drupal 8</h3>\n<p>This might come even more shocking for people having an idea what <a href=\"https://www.drupal.org/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener noreferrer\">Drupal</a> is. It’s an association of heavy CMS with high resource demand.</p>\n<p>Yet, do the following the sake of having your WOW moment yourself:</p>\n<ol>\n<li>Create a new workspace based on <a href=\"https://github.com/drupal-composer/drupal-project\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener noreferrer\">Drupal Composer</a> github repository</li>\n<li>Follow the instructions to run an installation from the cli or the web (you might need to read <a href=\"https://community.c9.io/t/setting-up-mysql/1718\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener noreferrer\">this MySQL</a> article if you don’t have the idea to see your <a href=\"https://help.ubuntu.com/community/EnvironmentVariables\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener noreferrer\">environment variables</a> from the command line.</li>\n<li>Profit from having a running Drupal 8 which uses <a href=\"https://getcomposer.org/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener noreferrer\">Composer</a> scripts for managing modules and dependencies to external libraries.</li>\n</ol>\n<p><span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;  max-width: 800px;\"\n    >\n      <a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/static/7399225c169809177731220f95770fdd/8ff1e/cloud9-editor-php-demo.png\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n    <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 46.75%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/png;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <picture>\n        <source\n          srcset=\"/static/7399225c169809177731220f95770fdd/01472/cloud9-editor-php-demo.webp 240w,\n/static/7399225c169809177731220f95770fdd/222bd/cloud9-editor-php-demo.webp 480w,\n/static/7399225c169809177731220f95770fdd/0cbce/cloud9-editor-php-demo.webp 800w\"\n          sizes=\"(max-width: 800px) 100vw, 800px\"\n          type=\"image/webp\"\n        />\n        <source\n          srcset=\"/static/7399225c169809177731220f95770fdd/0783d/cloud9-editor-php-demo.png 240w,\n/static/7399225c169809177731220f95770fdd/782f4/cloud9-editor-php-demo.png 480w,\n/static/7399225c169809177731220f95770fdd/8ff1e/cloud9-editor-php-demo.png 800w\"\n          sizes=\"(max-width: 800px) 100vw, 800px\"\n          type=\"image/png\"\n        />\n        <img\n          class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n          src=\"/static/7399225c169809177731220f95770fdd/8ff1e/cloud9-editor-php-demo.png\"\n          alt=\"Demo of Cloud9 with PHP\"\n          title=\"Demo of Cloud9 with PHP\"\n          loading=\"lazy\"\n        />\n      </picture>\n  </a>\n    </span></p>","fields":{"slug":"cloud9-editor","tagSlugs":["/tag/cloud/","/tag/drupal/","/tag/cloud-9/","/tag/tools/"]},"frontmatter":{"date":"2016-08-29T00:00:00+02:00","description":"Using Cloud9 for coding in the clouds.","tags":["Cloud","Drupal","Cloud9","Tools"],"title":"Cloud9 IDE","socialImage":null}}},"pageContext":{"isCreatedByStatefulCreatePages":false,"slug":"cloud9-editor"}}}